You are in an alley.
You can see a trashcan, a pigeon and a nest.
You can go southwest.
 You saunter out into the alley, but your keen urchin ears pick up the subtle rustle of feathers on the breeze... and you dive for cover behind the garbage cans.  Your instincts probably just saved your life, because, perched on the fence at the far end of the alley, sitting in a nest of gleaming urchin bones, is a pigeon.

A pigeon is no more than a nuisance for most city-dwellers, but these awful birds with their razor-sharp talons and insatiable appetites are certain death from above for urchins. You've known far too many urchin compatriots who've been carried off by pigeons, to become meals to their ghoulish fledglings.

Even from your vantage point behind the garbage cans, you can see the bird's nest is filled to brim with the small, delicate bones of urchins less quick than you.
