"I ain't got time to talk, little sister," he says. "I gotta get this guitar fixed before it's my time to go on stage."
> ask Fats about guitar

> ask Fats about guitar
"Wot kind of music does you play?" you ask.

"I play deep southern dixie-fried delta blues," says Hellbender Fats. "But it's not just music. I'm giving voice to a soul in torment. You mighta heard some of my more famous pieces 'The Seasonal Affective Disorder Blues' or 'My Baby Done Killed My Dog.'"

"Can't say that I have," you say. You don't know much about any music that isn't performed on a washtub bass or by blowing into a jug.

"I'd play a little for ya now," says Hellbender. "But I've busted the catgut strings on this ol' guitar and, if I can't get a replacement, I won't be playing nothing no more."
> ask Fats about catgut

> ask Fats about catgut
"Wot's wrong with yer strings?" you ask. "Is they broken?"

"Yeah, snapped clean through. I need some new catgut to fix 'em."

"Cat gut? Like, from a real cat?"

"Naw, that's just the name. Any kinda gut will do.  I just need some fibers from some animal gut to restring it."
> ask Fats about Papa

> ask Fats about Papa
"How 'bout that Papa Macaroni? Who's he think he is, eh?"

"I don't talk guff about Papa Macaroni," says Hellbender Fats. "He's been in a bad mood lately. They say he's been depressed, thinking about how much better the food was back home in Italy." He pauses, thinking. "That could be the basis of a good blues song right there. Maybe if my guitar wasn't busted."
> ask Fats about Tony

> ask Fats about Tony
