You can go east, north, west, south, northeast or southeast.
A small bare room, the walls are stained brick, the floor is worn concrete, lit by a dangling incandescent light bulb. Doors are set into the north, east, and west walls. Tony Macaroni leans against the wall next to the door to the east, glaring at you with disdain.

An aperture in the wall to the south leads to another room; you can hear excited whoops and shouts from within.
> ask Tony about moll

> ask Tony about moll
"Oy! So how 'bout your pop's moll? He's a looker, ain't he?" you say.

Tony shuffles his feet. "Yeah, I guess so. Pop says I gotta be nice ta him on account a' how he might be me mutter someday. But I still tink it's a little premature ta give him da authority to call out hits. I mean, he's just a college kid, fer chrissakes! Who's he gonna call out hits on? Some odder fraternity he don't like?"
> put shoelaces on plate

> put shoelaces on plate
You arrange the shoelaces tastefully on the plate.
> put sauce on shoelaces

> put sauce on shoelaces
You dump the Sauce American all over the plate of shoelaces. Now it totally looks like spaghetti!
> give spaghetti to Tony

> give spaghetti to Tony

"Oy, crumbum! Ya think yer boss would like this?" you say, holding out the plate of ersatz spaghetti.

Tony's face lights up. "Eyyyy, dat looks like a real plate o' Italian spaghett right dere! Dat's just what da boss needs!"

He steps aside. "Why dontcha jest go right on in an' give to him, eh, bambina?"
> e

> e

You are in an office.
You can see Papa Macaroni, goons, a gangster's moll, a Lord Wartington statue and a commemorative coin.
You can go west.
A dimmly lit but spacious room that clearly belongs to a man of taste and refinement. The walls are lines with sturdy bookshelves of quality black walnut and ornate portraits, the floor covered with plush green wall-to-wall carpet, and a luxurious bearskin rug lies at the foot of the majestic oak desk that dominates the room.   A roaring fire in the hearth casts ominous shadows over the faces of the gangsters assembled here.

Behind the desk sits a short squat old man in a pinstriped suit, surrounded by some half dozen surly mafia goons, cigars clamped between gold teeth, fedoras cocked at menacing angles, faces criss-crossed by various interesting and disturbing scars.

"'Ey, ey, ey, what's dis?" sneers a tall greasy-looking goon with a mouthful of gold teeth. "Who's dis kid, comin' in here, disrespectin' da boss? Ya dare come in here when da boss is feelin' sad, maybe we should send ya to sleep wit' da fishes, eh?"

"Ehhh, blow it out yer ear!" you say, "I is Lil' Ragamuffin, the roughest toughest street urchin an' nobody's sweetheart! And I ain't scared of you nimrods! First one ta try anything, I'll give 'em a round a' chin music they'll never ferget!"

The gangsters bristle visibly, their hands not so subtly reaching into their lapels as if to retrieve something lethal, but the old man behind the desk chuckles at your bravado.

"Dis kid, I like her," he says. The gangsters visibly relax. "You boys all settle down. Dis kid makes me laugh."
> x Papa

> x Papa
Papa Macaroni is a short old man, his languid eyes hidden deep within successive folds of facial wrinkles; he looks like a prune in a pin-striped suit.
> x goons

> x goons
A real bunch of ne'er-do-wells from the looks of them.
> x moll

> x moll
The gangster's moll is a young tow-headed man of the collegiate persuasion, dressed in a full-length raccoon fur coat and a straw boater and clutching a university pennant. He's draped over a chaise longue.
> x statue

> x statue
It's a kewpie doll in the effigy of a cartoon warthog, standing on his back trotters, wearing a little cap and sweater emblazoned with big Greek letters. He's holding up a commemorative brass coin in his fore-hoof.

"Oy, wot's this pig?" you say,.

"Ahem, that's not just any pig, sweetie," says the gangster's moll. "That's Lord Wartington, the mascot for my fraternity Tappa Kegga Bru! My pledge brothers have trusted me with the sacred duty of watching Lord Wartington over the holidays."

"...so it's a pig."

"LORD WARTINGTON. And I should die if anything were to besmirch him!"
> x coin

> x coin
A commemorative brass coin emblazoned with... something. You can't read, so it might as well be Greek to you.
> give spaghetti to Papa

> give spaghetti to Papa
"Oy, ya mook, how's about a nice big plate o' spaghetti?" you say, holding out your tray of shoelaces covered in sauce American.

Papa Macaroni's jaundiced eyes light up. "Mama mia! Spaghetti! That's exactly what I've been dreamin' of! Hand it over, small child."

You watch as Papa Macaroni happily slurps up the shoelaces. He pauses momentarily mid slurp.

"Dis spaghetti is pretty al dente," he mumbles, "What recipe is dis?"

"Uh... Spaghetti a la urchin," you say.

He nods as if that means anything and then returns to his slurping.  In minutes, the plate is clean and Papa Macaroni leans back in his chair with a contented grin on his face.

"Small child, you have done me a great favor by bringing me a taste of da old country. For this, I will grant you any boon within my power. Name it!"

"Alright! Listen, crumbum, you gots my pal Percy all locked up inna cage to fight in th' rattin' pit. I want you to lets him go."

Papa Macaroni shrugs his shoulders helplessly. "Alas! You ask the one thing I cannot do! The ratting pit bets make too much money. If I was to cancel the fight, we'd have to refund all da bets. And da Macaroni gang don't do refunds."
> take coin

> take coin
"Oy, buddy, wot's that o'er there? Issit a goldfish swallowin' contest?" you say, pointing behind the moll.

"Is it? Oh, rahther!" says the moll excitedly, twisting on his chaise longue to get a good look.  As he's distracted, you grab the coin out of Lord Wartington's trotters.
> ask Papa about moll

> ask Papa about moll
"So how's yer moll doin', eh?" you say, trying to make some small talk.

"Eeeey, Chester dere is da apple of my eye," says Papa Macaroni. "We met when I was roughin' up some of his professors fer protection money an' it was love at first sight.. just like when da moon hits yer eye lika big pizza pie! I love Chester so much I e'en gave him authority to call out hits. Some a' da boys don't like that, but bada bing whatcha gonna do about it?"

"Nothin', boss!" say the goons.

"Dat's right."
