You are in a restaurant.
You can see a gentleman patron and intestines.
You can go south, west, east or northeast.
A refined atmosphere fills the restaurant portion of the speakeasy, where classy diners sit around white clothed tables to sip fine wines and sample rarified Hors d'oeuvres.  Everyone is dressed in their finest evening wear.

Waiters constantly stream in and out of the swinging doors to the west, ferrying platters of food and bottles of wine from the kitchen.
> ne

> ne

You are in an atrium.
You can see a podium, Tony Macaroni and a goons.
You can go southwest or northeast.
A luxurious room with fancy red drapes on the walls and a red carpet on the floor that makes arriving customers truly feel like royalty.

There's an exit up to the street to the northeast.
"Well, well, well, looks like our guest don't like our hospitality," sneers Tony, emerging suddenly from the shadows and blocking your exit with his bulk. "Circle round, boys, don't let dis little sneak get away."

You start to back away from Tony, but then quickly realize your escape is blocked off as a gaggle of goons file into the room from the restaurant. They're all clutching pipe wrenches and billy clubs, ready to fight.

"See, I didn't mind ya runnin' around da club," continues Tony, "But when ya try to steal our newest rat? Ooo, dat's a different story. How we s'posed ta make a livin' if we ain't got no new rats fer da rattin' pit?"

"Blow it out yer ear, screw!" you say, eloquent as ever.
Tony chuckles.  "See, now dere's where I gots da problem. But we can work things out. Just hand o'er yer rat nice and easy an' maybe we'll let ya go wit'out bustin' yer kneecaps."

"'Course if Pop hadn't instituted that dumb requisition note system, den we'd all have guns ta just blow ya away! But I reckon we can do just as much damage roughin' ya up wit' our fists!"

He looks at you expectantly.
> shoot Tony

> shoot Tony
"Oy, reach fer th' sky, ya mugs!" you shout, whipping out your Chicago typewriter.

"Psst! Rags! Does that even have any bullets in it?" whispers Percy.

"Shut yer yap, Percy, them crumbs don't know that!" you hiss back. Then out loud: "Stand back, ya sad sacks, or I'll pump ya fulla more lead than a number 2 pencil!"

"Criminy, she's got a gun!" yelps Tony, raising his arms in surrender. "Ugh, if only pop hadn't instituted that stupid requisition note system, then we'd have some firepower too!  Stand down, boys, let her through! It ain't worth it!"

"That's right!" you say, skipping toward Tony but keeping your Chicago Typewriter trained on his forehead. "You dumb doras learned a thing 'er two about Lil' Ragamuffin today! Ain't no one who can stop me!"

With that, you sprint for the exit, leaving the gangsters cowering in your wake.

"So long, dewdroppers!" you cry, ducking your head and skittering between Tony's legs before he can react. "I is out like a whale oil lamp! Like I said, ain't no hoosegow built that can hold Lil' Ragamuffin.. or her pal Percy!"

"Really, Rags? Must you make such a production out of everything?"

You grin. "Good ol' Percy! Ain't it grand ta have you back!"

Percy can't help but smile. "Thanks, Rags. I feel the same."

And off you two go, urchin and rat, united again! When you've got a pal on your shoulder, the whole world is your trashcan buffet!
[state=Finished]
